    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overread in trx_iris_set_freq when setting frequencies for multiple channels\n\n### Summary\nThe `trx_iris_set_freq` function in `radio/IRIS/iris_lib.cpp` was accessing frequency configuration arrays without proper bounds checking. When the function was called with a configuration that had fewer channels than the hardware supported, it would read past the end of the `rx_freq` and `tx_freq` arrays, potentially causing undefined behavior or crashes.\n\nThis happened because the function was iterating through all available device channels (`getNumChannels()`) rather than just the configured channels, and had no bounds checking against the configuration arrays.\n\n### Changes\n- `radio/IRIS/iris_lib.cpp`: Modified `trx_iris_set_freq` function to only iterate through configured channels and added bounds checking against the configuration arrays.\n\nThe fix ensures that only configured channels are accessed and prevents buffer overreads when the configuration has fewer channels than the hardware supports.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce this issue:\n1. Configure an IRIS device with fewer channels than the hardware supports (e.g., configure 1 RX/TX channel on a device that supports 2)\n2. Call `trx_iris_set_freq` with this configuration\n3. The function would attempt to access `openair0_cfg[0].rx_freq[1]` and `openair0_cfg[0].tx_freq[1]` even though only index 0 is valid\n4. This could result in reading garbage values or causing a segmentation fault depending on memory layout\n\nWith the fix, the function now properly checks that both the hardware and configuration support the channel before accessing it.\n"
}